President Barack Obama announced his intent to nominate Janice Lehrer-Stein as a member of the National Council on Disability. Lehrer-Stein is a former labor and employment discrimination litigator and currently serves on the Board of Directors and Chair of the Audit Committee of Medical Research Charities. She is also a National Trustee of the Foundation Fighting Blindness and a member of the Board of Directors of Disability Rights Advocates. Lehrer-Stein has retinitis pigmentosa and is legally blind. She holds a Juris Doctor degree from the University of Toronto and a Bachelor of Arts degree from Yale University.

President Obama also announced his intent to appoint Richard J. Danzig and Daniel Meltzer as members of the President's Intelligence Advisory Board. Danzig is a senior advisor at multiple organizations, including the Center for a New American Security and the Center for Naval Analyses. He served as the 71st Secretary of the Navy during the Clinton Administration and has extensive experience in national security issues. Danzig holds degrees from Reed College, Yale Law School, and Oxford University.

Meltzer is currently the Story Professor of Law at Harvard Law School and previously served as Principal Deputy Counsel to President Obama at the White House. He has a background in practicing law and has served in various positions in the government. Meltzer is a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and holds degrees from Harvard College and Harvard Law School.